buginformation.description:
Consider this code:

                // ----------------------------------
                package p;

                public sealed class X permits Y, Z {}
                final class Y extends X {}
                final class Z extends X {}
                // ----------------------------------

                When I format it, it turns into this:

                // ----------------------------------
                package p;

                public sealed class X permits Y,Z {
                }

                final class Y extends X {
                }

                final class Z extends X {
                }
                // ----------------------------------

                Note the missing whitespace between Y,Z, which should be the default.

                There's a missing formatting option for the whitespace in the permits clause before and after commas, just like there is for the implements clause in
                Whitespace)Declarations)Classes

                I.e. similar to the preferences if org.eclipse.jdt.core.prefs:

                - org.eclipse.jdt.core.formatter.insert_space_before_comma_in_superinterfaces
                - org.eclipse.jdt.core.formatter.insert_space_after_comma_in_superinterfaces

The code below complies in javac, but produces the following error in ECJ:

                The method asList(T...) of type Arrays is not applicable as the formal varargs element type T is not accessible here


                import java.util.Arrays;
                import java.util.List;

                import javax.swing.JDialog;
                import javax.swing.JPanel;

                public class Snippet {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                var list = Arrays.asList(new JDialog(), new JPanel());
                }
                }

                The same happens with: Stream.of

                It can be worked-around using either:

                Arrays.(Component)asList(new JDialog(), new JPanel());
                Arrays.asList((Component) new JDialog(), new JPanel());

                In contrast, this works without a problem:

                List.of(new JDialog(), new JPanel());

                Due to the 2-parameter overload, showing that ECJ is able to successfully resolve the common base-type Component in this case.

                Details:
                * Java 11 compliance level
                * I'm running Eclipse 4.20 with AdoptOpenJDK 11.0.4+11

In the Code below

                public record A() {

                }

                class B extends A{

                }

                An error is thrown at 'extends A'. The error says that "The type B cannot subclass the final class A".

                as a result a quick fix is suggested to remove the final modifier from Class A.

                The error should be more specific to say that "The type B cannot subclass record A".

This program compiles just fine in javac, but not in Eclipse:

                // --------------------------------------
                package p;

                public class Test {

                interface I1(T) {}
                interface I2(X, T) extends I1(T) {}

                (T) void m() {
                I1(T) i1 = null;

                if (i1 instanceof I2(?, T) i2) {}
