Created attachment 287494
                Error details

                eclipse.buildId=4.22.0.I20211111-0910
                More details and full stack in the attached file.

                Sample code that caused the problem:

                public class Main {
                void main(Integer i) {
                Object a = switch (i) {
                default -) {
                yield i.toString();
                }
                }
                }
                }

                The error occurs when I paste it as a custom preview code in the java formatter preferences dialog. Then the preview feature stops working. I have to close Eclipse,
                remove the sample code from .metadata\.plugins\org.eclipse.jdt.ui\dialog_settings.xml and start again.

                The code doesn't cause problems when added as a class in a project. The difference is that the formatter doesn't know the kind of code so it tries different options
                and can't get it right because of the syntax error (missing semicolon). The error happens when the formatter tries to parse it as a module info with kind
                ASTParser.K_COMPILATION_UNIT.

                Oh, so another way to reproduce the problem is to paste the code into a module-info.java file in a project.

                There's no problem for example if "default -) i.toString();" is used instead of yield.

Raised by Remi Forax

                public class EclipseRecordBug {
                record Entry(T)(int value, Entry(T) entry) {

                Entry(int value, Entry entry) { // Entry is a raw type here

                }
                }
                }

import java.lang.invoke.MethodHandles;
                import java.lang.invoke.VarHandle;

                public class VarHandleBug {
                private static final VarHandle VH;
                static {
                var lookup = MethodHandles.lookup();
                try {
                VH = lookup.findVarHandle(VarHandleBug.class, "value", int.class);
                } catch (NoSuchFieldException | IllegalAccessException e) {
                throw new AssertionError(e);
                }
                }

                private volatile int value;

                public void test() {
                VH.compareAndSet(this, 2, 3); // (--- HERE
                }

                public static void main(String[] args) {
                new VarHandleBug().test();
                }
                }

                the compareAndSet() is typed
                VarHandle.compareAndSet(VarHandleBug,int,int)void
                instead of
                VarHandle.compareAndSet(VarHandleBug,int,int)Z

                the workaround is to introduce an unused boolean variable.
                boolean result = VH.compareAndSet(this, 2, 3);

                The way to compute a @PolymoprhicSignature as changed between Java 7 and Java 9, in Java 9 if the declared method returns a type which is not Object, then that
                return type should be used instead of trying to infer the return type from the context. So here boolean (the return type of compareAndSet) should be used instead of
                void the type inferred from the context.

                Thanks to Remi Forax for the above bug

Given the code

                sealed interface Shape {

                non-sealed class Square implements Shape {}

                record Circle() implements Shape {}

                sealed class Shape3D implements Shape {

                final class Box extends Shape3D {}

                final class Sphere extends Shape3D {}
                }
                }

                void sum(Shape s) {
                switch (s) {
                case Square q -) {}
                case Circle c -) {}
                case Shape3D d3 -) {}
                }
                }

                The switch statement is exhaustive. Gradle compiles it without an error. However, eclipse reports "An enhanced switch statement should be exhaustive; a default
                label expected" with a red squiggly under the 's' in 'switch (s)'. Adding a default makes the error go away.

                However, if we redefine Shape3D to be non-sealed or final (and remove Box and Sphere), then the compiler is happy.

                The compiler should not report the switch as non-exhaustive even if subtypes are present.

The following code snippet implements an enum lookup by some enum property:

                // -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                package p;

                import static java.util.function.Function.identity;

                import java.util.Map;
                import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;
                import java.util.stream.Collectors;
                import java.util.stream.Stream;

                public class Lookup {

                private static final Map(Class(?), Map(String, I)) LOOKUP = new ConcurrentHashMap()();

                @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
                static (E extends Enum(E) I) E lookupLiteral(Class(E) enumType, String literal) {
                return (E) LOOKUP.computeIfAbsent(enumType, t -)
                Stream.of(enumType.getEnumConstants()).collect(Collectors.(E, String, I)toMap(E::getLiteral, identity()))
                ).get(literal);
                }

                public static void main(String[] args) {
                System.out.println(Lookup.lookupLiteral(X.class, "a"));
                }

                interface I {
                String getLiteral();
                }

                enum X implements I {
                A("a");

                final String literal;

                X(String literal) {
                this.literal = literal;
                }

                @Override
                public String getLiteral() {
                return literal;
                }
                }
                }
                // -----------------------------------------------------------------------

