provide support for the new inline tag in javadoc
                @snippet for code snippets.

                This bug is to mainly support @snippet inline tag and add inline code snippets

                example given below

                /**
                * The following code shows how to use {@code println}:
                * {@snippet :
                * System.out.println("Hello world");
                * }
                */

provide support for the new inline tag in javadoc
                @snippet for external snippets.

                Here is the same example for an external snippet:
                /**
                * The following code shows how to use {@code println}:
                * {@snippet file="PrintlnExample.java" region="example"}
                */

                where PrintlnExample.java is a file containing:

                public class PrintlnExample {
                void print(String msg) {
                // @start region="example"
                System.out.println(msg);
                // @end
                }
                }

                This includes support for @start, @end and region.

Formatting a switch expression with a very long case statement does not wrap the cases. For example, with a width of 40:


                switch (color) {
                case RED, GREEN, BLACK, BLUE, CYAN, ORANGE, WHITE, PINK -) true;
                default -) false;
                }

                ...there doesn't appear to be a combination of settings to wrap the `case` line. It ought to be possible to wrap it, for example:

                switch (color) {
                case RED, GREEN, BLACK, BLUE, CYAN,
                ORANGE, WHITE, PINK -) true;
                default -) false;
                }

                Another example:

                switch (color) {
                case RED,
                GREEN,
                BLACK,
                BLUE,
                CYAN,
                ORANGE,
                WHITE,
                PINK -) true;
                default -) false;
                }

Consider:

                sealed class C permits D {}
                final class D extends C {}
                public class X {
                @SuppressWarnings("preview")
                static void foo(C ji) {
                switch (ji) { // non-exhaustive
                case D d : System.out.println("D"); break;
                };
                }
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                X.foo(new D());
                }
                }

                This should not be accepted but no error is thrown.

                However do note that a variant of this with abstract class should be accepted and it is being accepted correctly - ie C is abstract sealed with rest of the code as
                above.

Consider:

                sealed abstract class C permits D {}
                final class D extends C {}
                public class X {
                @SuppressWarnings("preview")
                static (T extends C) void foo(T ji) {
                switch (ji) { // exhaustive because C is sealed and abstract
                case D d : System.out.println("D"); break;
                };
                }
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                X.foo(new D());
                }
                }

                Error flagged : "An enhanced switch statement should be exhaustive; a default label expected"

                Since C is abstract and sealed, compiler should deduce that this is exhaustive.

                Similar case with interface as well [ie sealed interface C permits D]

