The spec is not very clear about pattern variables in 14.30.1:

                Any variable that is used but not declared in the guarding expression of a guarded pattern must either be final or effectively final (4.12.4).

                Does "but not declared" mean the pattern variable? Javac seems to think so. But ECJ reports an error with the following code:

                @SuppressWarnings("preview")
                Long foo(Number n) {
                return switch (n) {
                case (Long l) l.equals("0") -) {
                yield l++;
                }
                default -) throw new IllegalArgumentException();
                };
                }
                We get "Local variable l referenced from a guard must be final or effectively final" from ECJ but Javac happily allows it.

In certain cases of nested switch statement within a switch expression, ECJ reports an incorrect error. Code in case:

                public class X5 {
                public int foo(Integer arg0) {
                int result = 0;
                result = switch (arg0) {
                case Object p : {
                switch (arg0) {
                case Object p1 : {
                yield 6;
                }
                }
                }
                };
                return result;
                }
                }

                The error reported: A switch labeled block in a switch expression should not complete normally

                Without the inner switch statement and with the yield directly inside the case block everything works as expected.

As a result of code not being generated for the guard condition inside an instanceof expression, the code is totally ignored and doesn't have any effect
                when run. Here's a testcase:

                public class X6 {
                public static Object str = "a";
                public static void foo() {
                if (str instanceof (String a a == null)) {
                System.out.println(true);
                } else {
                System.out.println(false);
                }
                }
                public static void main(String[] argv) {
                foo();
                }
                }

                This should print false since a == null can never be true. But code compiled with ECJ always prints true, no matter what that condition is.

A super interface in a case pattern should be considered to be total but ECJ doesn't treat it as one. The following case reports an error that "A switch
                expression should have a default case".

                public static boolean foo(Integer n) {
                return switch (n) {
                case Integer x x.equals(10) -) {
                yield true;
                }
                case Comparable y -) {
                yield false;
                }
                };
                }

                Also the following code is accepted but should be rejected as a switch can't have both total pattern and default case.

                public static boolean foo(Integer n) {
                return switch (n) {
                case Integer x x.equals(10) -) {
                yield true;
                }
                case Comparable y -) {
                yield false;
                }
                default -) {
                yield false;
                }
                };
                }

                I am assuming both happen because the pattern "Comparable y" is not flagged as total.

